edits.response:
To show more than one result, you can iterate over the fetched data using a loop (e.g., `forEach`) and dynamically create HTML elements for each result. Here's how you can modify the code:

### /workspaces/ISYS3004_STAHURA_19174279_Asse1/2API.html

Update the JavaScript to display all user names from the fetched data.

````html
<!-- filepath: /workspaces/ISYS3004_STAHURA_19174279_Asse1/2API.html -->
<script>
  // ...existing code...
  fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users')
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(data => {
      const dataDiv = document.getElementById('data');
      if (data.length > 0) {
        // Clear the container
        dataDiv.innerHTML = '<h2>User List:</h2>';
        // Iterate over the data and append each user's name
        data.forEach(user => {
          const userElement = document.createElement('p');
          userElement.textContent = user.name; // Display the user's name
          dataDiv.appendChild(userElement);
        });
      } else {
        dataDiv.innerHTML = '<p>No data found.</p>';
      }
    })
    .catch(error => {
      console.error('Error fetching data:', error);
    });
</script>
````

### Summary of Changes:
1. Added a `forEach` loop to iterate over the fetched data.
2. Dynamically created a `<p>` element for each user's name and appended it to the `#data` container.
3. Ensured the container is cleared before appending new content.

